<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
During research on the type of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tornabene &amp; Wagner" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Tornabene &amp; Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="2013" class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Poaceae" genus="Pennisetum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Graminales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="articulare">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<pageBreakToken pageId="2" pageNumber="3" start="start">Pennisetum</pageBreakToken>
articulare
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Trin., an important discrepancy became apparent. The specimen has always been assumed to have been collected by Kyber who was on numerous expeditions with Ferdinand von Wrangel between 1821 and 1827 (
<bibRefCitation author="Wrangel, FP" journalOrPublisher="J. Madden and Co." pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 413" refId="B12" refString="Wrangel, FP, Sabine, E, 1840. Narrative of an Expedition to the Polar Sea, in the Years 1820, 1821, 1822 &amp; 1823. J. Madden and Co.: 1 - 413" title="Narrative of an Expedition to the Polar Sea, in the Years 1820, 1821, 1822 &amp; 1823." year="1840">Wrangel and Sabine 1840</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="International Documentation Company" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 66" refId="B8" refString="Soreng, RJ, Peterson, PM, Annable, CR, 1995. Trinius General Herbarium: Guide to the Microform Collection. International Documentation Company: 1 - 66" title="Trinius General Herbarium: Guide to the Microform Collection." year="1995">Soreng et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
). This would initially appear to be supported by the information contained on the Holotype label, &quot;Exped. Sub Navarrho F.P. de Wrangel&quot; and a small note in illegible German script labeled Kyber, 1827. However, the species was published in 1821, at least two years prior to when Kyber was reported to have arrived in the Pacific with Von Wrangel., (
<bibRefCitation author="Wrangel, FP" journalOrPublisher="J. Madden and Co." pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 413" refId="B12" refString="Wrangel, FP, Sabine, E, 1840. Narrative of an Expedition to the Polar Sea, in the Years 1820, 1821, 1822 &amp; 1823. J. Madden and Co.: 1 - 413" title="Narrative of an Expedition to the Polar Sea, in the Years 1820, 1821, 1822 &amp; 1823." year="1840">Wrangel and Sabine 1840</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
After an extensive review of the relevant literature, which revealed that Ferdinand von Wrangel was in the Marquesas Islands in mid-March 1818 with the Danish botanist Marten Wormskjold (
<bibRefCitation author="Golovnin, VM" journalOrPublisher="Hawaiian Historical Society, Honolulu, Hawaii" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 353" refId="B4" refString="Golovnin, VM, Wiswell, EL, 1979. Around the World on the Kamchatka, 1817-1819. Hawaiian Historical Society, Honolulu, Hawaii: 1 - 353" title="Around the World on the Kamchatka, 1817 - 1819." year="1979">Golvonin 1979</bibRefCitation>
), we have concluded that Marten Wormskjold likely collected the specimens during this time, leaving his collections with Von Wrangel to be delivered to Trinius for identification. This theory is substantiated by the fact the all of the writing on the original label is 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Trinius’">Trinius'</normalizedToken>
handwriting, except for 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kyber’s">Kyber's</normalizedToken>
note. Subsequently the specimen was believed to have been returned to Von Wrangel providing the opportunity in 1827 for Dr. Kyber, the previously presumed collector, to examine the specimen and make additional notes.
</paragraph>
